The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Nation | Nation Briefs
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                         NATION BRIEFS
                                      
	 New Delhi, July 30: An embarrassed BJP today tried to shrug off the irresponsible remarks made by Sushma Swaraj as her personal view.           Sushma, who refused to retract her charge, asserted the party had nothing to do with her personal views. Spokesperson Prakash Javadekar, without contradicting Sushma directly, said the party believes the terror incidents were an attack on India.                   
	 London (PTI): Britain has announced stricter immigration rules for students from India and elsewhere to prevent them from entering the country as students and then disappearing. Sources said the new system, known as Tier 4, will be more transparent.                   
	 New Delhi (PTI): Chief Justice of India K.G. Balakrishnan has recused himself from hearing the multi-crore provident fund scam in Uttar Pradesh that allegedly involves judges, including one from the Supreme Court. The case will now be heard on August 1 by a bench headed by Justice B.N. Aggrawal, the senior-most judge of the apex court.                  
	 Panaji (PTI): Fiona Mackeown, mother of British teenager Scarlett Keeling, who was found dead on Goas Anjuna beach, is expected to depose before the CBI next week, her counsel said.                  
	 Mumbai (PTI): Air intelligence sleuths arrested a Zambian national on Tuesday night for allegedly possessing heroin worth Rs 1.38 crore. He was going to Johannesburg by a South African Airlines flight and had concealed the drugs in the false bottom of his suitcase.                   
	 Thiruvananthapuram (PTI): Kerala chief minister V.S. Achuthanandan on Wednesday announced that kits worth Rs 50, containing 2kg rice, sugar, tea and chilli, would be supplied free to BPL cardholders during the forthcoming Onam season. The cabinet has also decided to provide free ration to people affected by fever in Kasargod district, he said.                                                                                                                         
